#AAPIHeritageMonth  originally used to educate & make demands about material issues in our communities is now used to placate and redirect attention from our lack of access to housing healthcare quality public education & the military/police violence against #AAPI folks

#AAPIHeritageMonth  Today for AAPI Heritage Month we are spotlighting South Korean Novelist Pak Kyongni.  Pak Kyongni is  known for her 20 volume epic Toji. Toji is about a group of Koreans and how they were affected by Japanese occupation from 1897 to 1945. https://t.co/igrtB7CJ2f

#AAPIHeritageMonth Chandrasekhara Venkata Raman won the Nobel Prize for Physics in 1930¬†for his pioneering work on scattering of light. He also was the first to investigate the harmonic nature of the sound of the Indian drums such as the tabla and the mridangam. https://t.co/CWnEHFoguk

#AAPIHeritageMonth Dr. Mabel Ping-Hua Lee was a prominent figure in NYC's suffragist movement. The passage of the 19th Amendment guaranteed the right to vote to all female citizens; however Lee still couldn't vote via the Chinese Exclusion Act. More here: https://t.co/azgKtXJkqH https://t.co/wT9lUYoGds

#AAPIHeritageMonth Happy to see @APA_Planning recognize @UCLALuskin's Professor Paul Ong as an AAPI who has advanced the field of urban planning! It's been a great honor to work with him and learn about his contributions towards greater equity and inclusion in our cities.
